In order to eliminate the interference of other factors, only Na2SeO3 was used to treat cowpea seedlings to assess the selenium effects on susceptibility of T. cinnabarinus to fenpropathrin. When the concentration of Na2SeO3 was 20 μM, the absorption capacity of cowpea leaves reached saturation, and 20 μM Na2SeO3 had no obvious lethal effects to T. cinnabarinus (Fig. S3). When spraying with different concentrations of fenpropathrin, the mortalities of T. cinnabarinus treated with 20 μM Na2SeO3 were significantly higher than that of control (Fig. 5
                        a). The LC50 of T. cinnabarinus was reduced from 746.77 mg·L−1 to 332.19 mg·L−1, meant Na2SeO3 enhanced 2.25-fold toxicity of fenpropathrin against T. cinnabarinus (Table 1
                        ). Generally, fenpropathrin was used by spraying, while Na2SeO3 was used by root irrigation. This difference is the main obstacle for combined application of fenpropathrin and Na2SeO3. If Na2SeO3 was still used in the traditional way to increase the acaricidal effect of fenpropathrin, it would be inconvenient for practice and accumulation of Na2SeO3 in the leaves. In order to achieve the purpose of applying Na2SeO3 and fenpropathrin simultaneously, CDs was selected to deliver Na2SeO3 for leaf spraying.

To explain why selenium can increase the toxicity of fenpropathrin, the activity changes of three detoxification enzyme (P450s, GSTs, CarEs) of mites were detected after exposure to 20 μM Na2SeO3. It was found that selenium only has an inhibitory effect on P450 (Table 3
                        ). Subsequently, the expressions of previously discovered six P450 genes which had the capacity of detoxifying fenpropathrin were quantified by qPCR (Shi et al., 2016). The expression of three P450 genes (CYP389B1, CYP392A26, CYP392A28) were down-regulated in the Na2SeO3 treatments (Fig. 6
                        ). Thus, we believe that different P450 genes may have different responses to selenium.
